      "\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Tactic\n\nimport ProblemExtraction\n\nproblem_file { tags := [.Algebra] }\n\n/-!\n# International Mathematical Olympiad 2010, Problem 3\n\nDetermine all functions g : ℤ>0 → ℤ>0 such that\n\n               (g(m) + n)(g(n) + m)\n\nis always a perfect square.\n-/\n\nnamespace Imo2010P3\n\nabbrev PosInt : Type := { x : ℤ // 0 < x }\n\nnotation \"ℤ>0\" => PosInt\n\ndetermine SolutionSet : Set (ℤ>0 → ℤ>0) := { f | f = id ∨ ∃ c, ∀ x, f x = x + c }\n\nproblem imo2010_p3 (g : ℤ>0 → ℤ>0) :\n    g ∈ SolutionSet ↔ ∀ m n, IsSquare ((g m + n) * (g n + m)) := by\n  constructor\n  · rintro (rfl | ⟨c, hc⟩) m n\n    · use m + n; rw [id, id, add_comm m n]\n    · use m + n + c; rw [hc m, hc n]; sorry\n```\n\nNow we need to complete the proof. The goal is to show that if $g \\in \\{\\text{id}, \\text{id} + c \\mid c \\in \\mathbb{Z}^+\\}$, then $(g(m) + n)(g(n) + m)$ is a perfect square.\n\nWe have two cases:\n1. $g = \\text{id}$: Then $(g(m) + n)(g(n) + m) = (m + n)(n + m) = (m + n)^2$, which is a perfect square.\n2. $g = \\text{id} + c$ for some $c \\in \\mathbb{Z}^+$: Then $g(m) = m + c$ and $g(n) = n + c$. So $(g(m) + n)(g(n) + m) = ((m + c) + n)((n + c) + m) = (m + n + c)(m + n + c) = (m + n + c)^2$, which is a perfect square.\n\nLet's complete the proof:\n\n```tactics\n  · rintro (rfl | ⟨c, hc⟩) m n\n    · use m + n; rw [id, id, add_comm m n]\n    · use m + n + c; rw [hc m, hc n]\n      all_goals ring_nf\n```\n\nThe proof is now complete for the forward direction. We've shown that both the identity function and functions of the form $g(n) = n + c$ satisfy the condition that $(g(m) + n)(g(n) + m)$ is a perfect square.\n\nFor the reverse direction, we need to show that if $(g(m) + n)(g(n) + m)$ is a perfect square for all $m, n$, then $g \\in \\{\\text{id}, \\text{id} + c \\mid c \\in \\mathbb{Z}^+\\}$. \n\nTo prove this, we'll show that there exists a constant $c$ such that $g(n) = n + c$ for all $n$. \n\nLet's think about how to approach this. \