      "\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Tactic\n\nimport ProblemExtraction\n\nproblem_file { tags := [.Algebra] }\n\n/-!\n# International Mathematical Olympiad 2010, Problem 3\n\nDetermine all functions g : ℤ>0 → ℤ>0 such that\n\n               (g(m) + n)(g(n) + m)\n\nis always a perfect square.\n-/\n\nnamespace Imo2010P3\n\nabbrev PosInt : Type := { x : ℤ // 0 < x }\n\nnotation \"ℤ>0\" => PosInt\n\ndetermine SolutionSet : Set (ℤ>0 → ℤ>0) := { f | f = id ∨ ∃ c, ∀ x, f x = x + c }\n\nproblem imo2010_p3 (g : ℤ>0 → ℤ>0) :\n    g ∈ SolutionSet ↔ ∀ m n, IsSquare ((g m + n) * (g n + m)) := by\n  constructor\n  · rintro (rfl | ⟨c, hc⟩) m n\n    · use m + n; rw [id, id, add_comm m n]\n    · use m + n + c; rw [hc m, hc n]; sorry\n```\n\nWe need to complete the proof. The goal is to show that \\( g \\in \\text{SolutionSet} \\) if and only if \\( \\forall m n, \\text{IsSquare}((g m + n) \\cdot (g n + m)) \\).\n\nThe forward direction is given. If \\( g \\in \\text{SolutionSet} \\), then either \\( g = \\text{id} \\) or \\( g(x) = x + c \\) for some \\( c \\). In either case, we can verify that \\( (g(m) + n)(g(n) + m) \\) is a perfect square.\n\nFor the reverse direction, we need to show that if \\( (g(m) + n)(g(n) + m) \\) is a perfect square for all \\( m, n \\), then \\( g \\) must be either the identity function or of the form \\( g(x) = x + c \\).\n\nLet's complete the proof.\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Tactic\n\nimport ProblemExtraction\n\nproblem_file { tags := [.Algebra] }\n\n/-!\n# International Mathematical Olympiad 2010, Problem 3\n\nDetermine all functions g : ℤ>0 → ℤ>0 such that\n\n               (g(m) + n)(g(n) + m)\n\nis always a perfect square.\n-/\n\nnamespace Imo2010P3\n\nabbrev PosInt : Type := { x : ℤ // 0 < x }\n\nnotation \"ℤ>0\" => PosInt\n\ndetermine SolutionSet : Set (ℤ>0 → ℤ>0) := { f | f = id ∨ ∃ c, ∀ x, f x = x + c }\n\nproblem imo2010_p3 (g : ℤ>0 → ℤ>0) :\n    g ∈ SolutionSet ↔ ∀ m n, IsSquare ((g m + n) * (g n + m)) := by\n  constructor\n  · -- Assume g ∈ SolutionSet, prove ∀ m n, IsSquare ((g m + n) * (g n + m))\n    rintro (rfl | ⟨c, hc⟩) m n\n    · -- Case g = id\n      use m + n\n      rw [id, id]\n      all_goals ring\n    · -- Case g(x) = x + c\n      use m + n + c\n      rw [hc m, hc n]\n      all_goals ring\n```\n\nNow, we need to prove the reverse direction. Assume \\( \\forall m n, \\text{IsSquare}((g m + n) \\cdot (g n + m)) \\), prove \\( g \\in \\text{SolutionSet} \\).\n\n```tactics\n  · -- Assume ∀ m n, IsSquare ((g m + n) * (g n + m)), prove g ∈ SolutionSet\n    intro h\n```\n\nNow, we need to show that \\( g \\) is either the identity function or of the form \\( g(x) = x + c \\).\n\nTo prove this, let's consider specific values of \\( m \\) and \\( n \\).\n\nFirst, let's take \\( m = n = 1 \\). Then \\( (g(1) + 1)(g(1) + 1) = (g(1) + 1)^2 \\), which is a perfect square. This is trivial.\n\nNow, let's take \\( m = 1 \\), \\( n = 2 \\). Then \\( (g(1) + 2)(g(2) + 1) \\) is a perfect square.\n\nSimilarly, for \\( m = 2 \\), \\( n = 1 \\), we get \\( (g(2) + 1)(g(1) + 2) \\), which is the same as above.\n\nNow, for arbitrary \\( m, n \\), we need to show that \\( (g(m) + n)(g(n) + m) \\) being a perfect square forces \\( g \\) to be of the claimed form.\n\nOne approach is to set \\( m = n \\). Then \\( (g(m) + m)(g(m) + m) = (g(m) + m)^2 \\), which is a perfect square. This is trivial.\n\nAnother approach is to set \\( n = 1 \\). Then for any \\( m \\), \\( (g(m) + 1)(g(1) + m) \\) is a perfect square.\n\nLet's fix \\( m \\) and let \\( n \\) vary. For a fixed \\( m \\), as \\( n \\) varies, we get different perfect squares.\n\nOne idea is to set \\( m = n \\). Then, as we saw, this gives \\( (g(m) + m)^2 \\), which is a perfect square.\n\nAnother idea is to set \\( m = 1 \\). Then for any \\( n \\), \\( (g(1) + n)(g(n) + 1) \\) is a perfect square.\n\nLet's suppose that \\( g \\) is not of the form \\( x \\mapsto x + c \\). Then there exist \\( a, b \\) such that \\( g(a) \\neq a + c \\) and \\( g