Left side: `(m + c + n) * (n + c + m)`
= `(m + n + c) * (m + n + c)`
= Right side

So we need to expand the left side and show it equals the right side.

```tactics
ring
```

The `ring` tactic is powerful enough to expand polynomial expressions and prove equalities in commutative rings. Here, it will expand the left side as `(m + n + c) * (m + n + c)` and the right side is already in that form, so `ring` will verify they are the same.

The complete proof is concise because the algebra is straightforward. The key insight is that when `g(x) = x + c`, the expression `(g(m) + n)(g(n) + m)` simplifies to `(m + n + c)²`, which is a perfect square.
